gh 1.1.0.9000
  • Reference
  • Changelog

GitHub API

Source: R/package.R
gh.Rd

Minimal wrapper to access GitHub's API.

This is an extremely minimal client. You need to know the API to be able to use this client. All this function does is:

  • Try to substitute each listed parameter into endpoint, using the :parameter notation.

  • If a GET request (the default), then add all other listed parameters as query parameters.

  • If not a GET request, then send the other parameters in the request body, as JSON.

  • Convert the response to an R list using jsonlite::fromJSON().

gh(
  endpoint,
  ...,
  per_page = NULL,
  .token = NULL,
  .destfile = NULL,
  .overwrite = FALSE,
  .api_url = NULL,
  .method = "GET",
  .limit = NULL,
  .accept = "application/vnd.github.v3+json",
  .send_headers = NULL,
  .progress = TRUE
)

Arguments

endpoint

GitHub API endpoint. Must be one of the following forms:

  • METHOD path, e.g. GET /rate_limit,

  • path, e.g. /rate_limit,

  • METHOD url, e.g. GET https://api.github.com/rate_limit,

  • url, e.g. https://api.github.com/rate_limit.

If the method is not supplied, will use .method, which defaults to "GET".
...

Name-value pairs giving API parameters. Will be matched into endpoint placeholders, sent as query parameters in GET requests, and as a JSON body of POST requests. If there is only one unnamed parameter, and it is a raw vector, then it will not be JSON encoded, but sent as raw data, as is. This can be used for example to add assets to releases. Named NULL values are silently dropped, and named NA values trigger an error.
per_page

Number of items to return per page. If omitted, will be substituted by max(.limit, 100) if .limit is set, otherwise determined by the API (never greater than 100).
.token

Authentication token. Defaults to GITHUB_PAT or GITHUB_TOKEN environment variables, in this order if any is set. See gh_token() if you need more flexibility, e.g. different tokens for different GitHub Enterprise deployments.
.destfile

Path to write response to disk. If NULL (default), response will be processed and returned as an object. If path is given, response will be written to disk in the form sent.
.overwrite

If .destfile is provided, whether to overwrite an existing file. Defaults to FALSE.
.api_url

Github API url (default: https://api.github.com). Used if endpoint just contains a path. Defaults to GITHUB_API_URL environment variable if set.
.method

HTTP method to use if not explicitly supplied in the endpoint.
.limit

Number of records to return. This can be used instead of manual pagination. By default it is NULL, which means that the defaults of the GitHub API are used. You can set it to a number to request more (or less) records, and also to Inf to request all records. Note, that if you request many records, then multiple GitHub API calls are used to get them, and this can take a potentially long time.
.accept

The value of the Accept HTTP header. Defaults to "application/vnd.github.v3+json" . If Accept is given in .send_headers, then that will be used. This paramter can be used to provide a custom media type, in order to access a preview feature of the API.
.send_headers

Named character vector of header field values (except Authorization, which is handled via .token). This can be used to override or augment the default User-Agent header: "https://github.com/r-lib/gh".
.progress

Whether to show a progress indicator for calls that need more than one HTTP request.

Value

Answer from the API as a gh_response object, which is also a list. Failed requests will generate an R error. Requests that generate a raw response will return a raw vector.

See also

Useful links:

  • https://github.com/r-lib/gh#readme

  • Report bugs at https://github.com/r-lib/gh/issues

gh_gql() if you want to use the GitHub GraphQL API, gh_whoami() for details on GitHub API token management.

Examples

if (identical(Sys.getenv("IN_PKGDOWN"), "true")) (if (getRversion() >= "3.4") withAutoprint else force)({ # examplesIf
## Repositories of a user, these are equivalent
gh("/users/hadley/repos")
gh("/users/{username}/repos", username = "hadley")

## Starred repositories of a user
gh("/users/hadley/starred")
gh("/users/{username}/starred", username = "hadley")
}) # examplesIf

#>     "body": "I'm noticing the following unexpected behaviour in inner_join()'s when joining by a matrix variable. \r\n\r\nConsider the following two tibbles:\r\n\r\n```r\r\nlibrary(dplyr)\r\n( t1 <- tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 3*16 + 1)), ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE) ) )\r\n( t2 <- tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(rep(2, 256), 0:255)), ncol = 2), y = 0:255 ) )\r\n```\r\n```\r\n# A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n  x[,1] [,2] \r\n  <raw> <raw>\r\n1 02    31   \r\n```\r\n```\r\n# A tibble: 256 x 2\r\n   x[,1] [,2]      y\r\n   <raw> <raw> <int>\r\n 1 02    00        0\r\n 2 02    01        1\r\n 3 02    02        2\r\n 4 02    03        3\r\n 5 02    04        4\r\n 6 02    05        5\r\n 7 02    06        6\r\n 8 02    07        7\r\n 9 02    08        8\r\n10 02    09        9\r\n# … with 246 more rows\r\n```\r\n\r\nThus t1 matches a single row in t2, and I would expect inner_join(t1,t2) to return a single row. However I'm getting two rows, corresponding to y = 49 (as expected) and y = 63 (?).\r\n\r\n```r\r\ninner_join(t1,t2)\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n  x[,1] [,2]      y\r\n  <raw> <raw> <int>\r\n1 02    31       49\r\n2 02    31       63\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere are some other examples with single column tibbles, some producing unexpected matchings.\r\n\r\n1. Matching, as expected\r\n\r\n```r\r\ninner_join(\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 49)), ncol = 2) ),\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 49)), ncol = 2) )\r\n)\r\n```\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n  x[,1] [,2] \r\n  <raw> <raw>\r\n1 02    31   \r\n```\r\n\r\n2. Matching, unexpectedly:\r\n\r\n```r\r\ninner_join(\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 49)), ncol = 2) ),\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 63)), ncol = 2) )\r\n)\r\n```\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n  x[,1] [,2] \r\n  <raw> <raw>\r\n1 02    31   \r\n```\r\n\r\n3. Matching, unexpectedly:\r\n\r\n```r\r\ninner_join(\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 49)), ncol = 2) ),\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 64)), ncol = 2) )\r\n)\r\n```\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n  x[,1] [,2] \r\n  <raw> <raw>\r\n1 02    31   \r\n```\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 0 x 1\r\n# … with 2 variables: x[,1] <raw>, [,2] <raw>\r\n```\r\n\r\n4. Not matching, as expected:\r\n\r\n```r\r\ninner_join(\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 49)), ncol = 2) ),\r\n        tibble( x = matrix( as.raw(c(2, 65)), ncol = 2) )\r\n)\r\n```\r\n5. An example with vector columns. Everything works fine:\r\n\r\n```r\r\nt1 <- tibble( x = as.raw(3*16 + 1) )\r\nt2 <- tibble( x = as.raw(0:255), y = 0:255 )\r\ninner_join(t1,t2)\r\n```\r\n```\r\nJoining, by = \"x\"\r\n# A tibble: 1 x 2\r\n  x         y\r\n  <raw> <int>\r\n1 31       49\r\n```\r\n6. #>     "body": "Closes #5428 \r\n\r\nThe `map()` and `as_tibble()` calls in `n_distinct()` are fairly slow when called repeatedly (added in https://github.com/tidyverse/dplyr/pull/5072).\r\n\r\nThis PR refactors `n_distinct()` to avoid tibble and `map()` and instead only use vctrs. I imagine this will be further improved with hybrid eval, but this should help significantly for now. I don't think it should change any behavior of `n_distinct()`.\r\n\r\nBelow is an adjusted example from #5428. It reduces the number of rows from 50,000,000 down to a more reasonable 500,000. The example there was a bit extreme to run on 50 million rows, but I imagine that it should at least work now.\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(tidyverse)\r\n\r\nset.seed(123)\r\ntable_size <- 500000\r\n\r\ndates <- seq(as.Date('2020/07/01'), as.Date('2020/07/18'), by = \"day\")\r\n\r\ntable_tbl <- tibble(\r\n  column_1 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  date = sample(x = dates, size = table_size, replace = TRUE),\r\n  column_3 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_4 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_5 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_6 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_7 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T)\r\n)\r\n\r\ntbl <- group_by(table_tbl, column_1, date, column_3, column_4, column_5)\r\n```\r\n\r\n```r\r\n# before\r\nbench::mark(\r\n  expr = summarise(tbl, ndist = n_distinct(column_6, column_7), .groups = \"drop_last\")\r\n)\r\n#> Warning: Some expressions had a GC in every iteration; so filtering is disabled.\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 6\r\n#>   expression      min   median `itr/sec` mem_alloc `gc/sec`\r\n#>   <bch:expr> <bch:tm> <bch:tm>     <dbl> <bch:byt>    <dbl>\r\n#> 1 expr          1.76m    1.76m   0.00947     130MB     4.87\r\n\r\n# after\r\nbench::mark(\r\n  expr = summarise(tbl, ndist = n_distinct(column_6, column_7), .groups = \"drop_last\")\r\n)\r\n#> Warning: Some expressions had a GC in every iteration; so filtering is disabled.\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 6\r\n#>   expression      min   median `itr/sec` mem_alloc `gc/sec`\r\n#>   <bch:expr> <bch:tm> <bch:tm>     <dbl> <bch:byt>    <dbl>\r\n#> 1 expr          8.74s    8.74s     0.114     130MB     4.69\r\n```\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-07-21 by the [reprex package](https://reprex.tidyverse.org) (v0.3.0)<\/sup>",

#>     "body": "I'm sure there are some design decisions in the way `bind_rows()` handles `NA`, `NULL` and zero-length list elements when creating the final `tbl_df`. However, I would like to note the differences between `dplyr::bind_rows()`, `do.call(rbind, .)` and `data.table::rbindlist()` because it appears that {dplyr} has the most undesirable and unpredictable behavior of all 3 options.\r\n\r\nIn all of the test cases below I would, at minimum, expect the result to have 2 rows and 2 columns. Ideally, it would also preserve the column order based on the elements and replace all zero-length elements with NA (i.e. `NULL` and zero length vectors like `integer(0)` or `character()`).\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(data.table, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\nlibrary(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Happy path test case (preserves all elements as-is)**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = \"A\", b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\nbind_rows(l)\r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 A         1\r\n#> 2 B         2\r\n\r\ndo.call(rbind, l)\r\n#>      a   b\r\n#> [1,] \"A\" 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\" 2\r\n\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE)\r\n#>    a b\r\n#> 1: A 1\r\n#> 2: B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**All NA elements in a list (row)**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NA, b = NA)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 <NA>     NA\r\n#> 2 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a   b \r\n#> [1,] NA  NA\r\n#> [2,] \"B\" 2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#>       a  b\r\n#> 1: <NA> NA\r\n#> 2:    B  2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**All NULL elements in list**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NULL, b = NULL)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and retains NULL values\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a    b   \r\n#> [1,] NULL NULL\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"  2\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE)\r\n#>    a b\r\n#> 1: B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**A single NULL element**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NULL, b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# preserves first row, but flips column order\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>       b a    \r\n#>   <dbl> <chr>\r\n#> 1     1 <NA> \r\n#> 2     2 B\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and retains NULL value\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a    b\r\n#> [1,] NULL 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"  2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and returns NA value in place of NULL\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#> Warning in rbindlist(l, fill = TRUE): Column 1 ['a'] of item 1 is length 0. This\r\n#> (and 0 others like it) has been filled with NA (NULL for list columns) to make\r\n#> each item uniform.\r\n#>       a b\r\n#> 1: <NA> 1\r\n#> 2:    B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**A single length zero element**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = character(0), b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\ndo.call(rbind, l)\r\n#>      a           b\r\n#> [1,] Character,0 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and returns NA in place of zero-length element\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#> Warning in rbindlist(l, fill = TRUE): Column 1 ['a'] of item 1 is length 0. This\r\n#> (and 0 others like it) has been filled with NA (NULL for list columns) to make\r\n#> each item uniform.\r\n#>       a b\r\n#> 1: <NA> 1\r\n#> 2:    B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-07-21 by the [reprex package](https://reprex.tidyverse.org) (v0.3.0)<\/sup>\r\n",

If I try to do group_by and then calculate distinct combintations with function n_distinct (in summarise) the calculation freezes. 1.3.959\r\n![htop_screenshot](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4153099/88039177-e7cc4400-cb4f-11ea-82de-eb776de3c7d1.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nReproducible snippet is #>     "body": "EDIT: @hadley identified the underlying issue is with grouping rather than summarize. See his post below\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile creating new columns using `mutate` or `summarize`, I'd like to be able to add the `label` attribute to each column so that I can add additional context to my columns at the time of creation. A useful [stackoverflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27347548/r-assign-variable-labels-of-data-frame-columns) supplied info on how to do this with `mutate`, however I've found that summarize drops the column attributes after creation (please see reprex below). \r\n\r\nHaving labels makes my data so much more understandable, and allows my customers (also R users) to get everything they need when using `view`/`View`:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"800\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2020-07-20 at 9 36 24 AM\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18296227/87962728-82535700-ca6c-11ea-921a-cf2d3dd36908.png\">\r\n \r\n---\r\n\r\nBrief description of the problem:\r\nWhile `mutate` and an ungrouped `summarize` maintain column attributes such as `label`, a grouped `summarize` does not.\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(magrittr)\r\nlibrary(tibble)\r\nlibrary(dplyr)\r\n#> \r\n#> Attaching package: Horse Power Ratio')) %>%\r\n  dplyr::pull() %>%\r\n  Hmisc::label()\r\n#> [1] \"Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio\"\r\n\r\n# Ungrouped summarize works as expected\r\nmtcars %>%\r\n #>     "body": "Hi, \r\n\r\nIt would be great if join commands had the possibility to update values. \r\n\r\nFor example, I am working with data frame \"m\" and want to update the \"x\" values for some NA cases using another data frame \"y\".  Join commands will generate two columns x.x and x.y. Then, I would have to mutate values to update variables in this new, larger data.frame. \r\n\r\nHowever, if there was an update = T option, the new data.frame could automatically update NA values from the master data-set with the columns that have the same name in the using data set. Then, no new columns will be generated, I will be working in a smaller data-set and there would be no need to do any extra steps. \r\n\r\nThere could also be a conflict option to also manage the cases in which there are values in both the master and using data set. For example, if conflict = F, then when there are values in both master and using values then master data is retained, and nothing is changed in the column for rows that are present in master and using data. However, if conflict = T then the data from the using data set is retained. \r\n\r\nIn STATA this is part of the  [merge](https://www.stata.com/manuals13/dmerge.pdf) command. Some people have been asking the same and making some workarounds [example](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51572462/update-replace-values-in-dataframe-with-tidyverse-join). \r\n \r\nThank you once again for dplyr.\r\n\r\n```r\r\nm <- data.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x = c(4, 4, NA))\r\nu <- data.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x = c(5, 5, 5))\r\n\r\n# Current results\r\nm %>% full_join(u, by = \"id\")\r\n\r\n# With update = T we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(4,4,5))\r\n\r\n# With update = T and conflict = T we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(5,5,5))\r\n# With update = T and conflict = F we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(4,4,5))\r\n\r\n\r\n```\r\n",

I know that row names on tibbles are deprecated (which I disagree with but that is beside the point) but I think that for now, given that someone wants to continue using this deprecated feature, functions like mutate should not drop rownames in cases by default where the user wants to keep them.  There are constructs outside of the tidyverse that still use rownames; for example the bioconductor object 'eset' uses them in important ways and there are tools that take esets and not more modern bioconductor objects.   So if I want to use tibbles and dplyr verbs when constructing esets I have to do inconvenient workarounds, or not use dplyr.   So what I want is for tidyverse functions to preserve rownames wherever possible, even though I know it is not possible with certain things (like joins where rows are added). \r\n\r\n\r\nHere is a simple example: \r\n```r\r\nlibrary(tidyverse)\r\nsmall_tibble <- mpg[1:3,1:3]\r\nrownames(small_tibble) <- c(\"snap\",\"cracke\",\"pop\")\r\nprint(rownames(small_tibble)) #setting rownames was successful\r\nsmall_tibble_mutated <- small_tibble %>% mutate(displ = displ^2)\r\nprint(rownames(small_tibble_mutated)) #rownames disappeared\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "It would be incredible if you could specify which kind of duplicates in the join variable(s) is(are) acceptable as in [the STATA merge command](https://www.stata.com/manuals13/dmerge.pdf). \r\n\r\nThis means having the possibility to decide whether it's ok to have: \r\n- Duplicates in the join variables of the master data but not in the join variables of the using data (a m:1 join)\r\n- Duplicates in the join variables of the using data but not in the join variables of the master data (a 1:m join)\r\n- Duplicates in both cases (an m:m join)\r\n- No duplicates (a 1:1 join)\r\n\r\nI work in education, and some times data-sets were poorly digitized because some students appear to have been enrolled in more than one school (duplicates in the join variable).  When that happens both in the master and using data, those students multiply exponentially in the resulting data-frame, as it happens now with, for example, left_join.  You may not want that. Also, if you are not cautious enough, you may not pay attention to duplicate students, that \"ninjaly\" add more observations to your results. \r\n\r\nSTATA used to have the same issue and only had two commands \"merge\" or \"join\" somehow similar to R, and did not let you decide when duplicates are acceptable (i.e duplicate information in the using data when merging students to school characteristics, school id is the join variable) and when it may not be acceptable (i.e duplicate information in the master and using data when merging a student list to a student characteristic, student id is the join variable). At some point, they made that feature feasible and it's great because it allows you to merge and make quality control in one single step. \r\n\r\nThank you for your time and amazing work. Hope this helps. \r\n",

#>     "body": "The ntile() function in dplyr 1.0.0 gives different results than in version 0.8.3.  Looking at the function code, it has changed a great deal.  I show both functions in my reprex.  ntile_083 scales us as the value of n increases, but ntile1_100 does not, its output is invariant to n (as long as n >= x).  This is a big change in the output.  Was this the intented result?\r\n\r\n```r\r\nntile_083 <- function (x = row_number(), n) {\r\n  len <- sum(!is.na(x))\r\n  if (len == 0L) {\r\n    rep(NA_integer_, length(x))\r\n  } else {\r\n    as.integer(floor(n * (row_number(x) - 1)/len + 1))\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\nntile_100 <- function (x = row_number(), n) {\r\n  if (!missing(x)) {\r\n    x <- row_number(x)\r\n  }\r\n  len <- length(x) - sum(is.na(x))\r\n  n <- as.integer(floor(n))\r\n  if (len == 0L) {\r\n    rep(NA_integer_, length(x))\r\n  } else {\r\n    n_larger <- as.integer(len%%n)\r\n    n_smaller <- as.integer(n - n_larger)\r\n    size <- len/n\r\n    larger_size <- as.integer(ceiling(size))\r\n    smaller_size <- as.integer(floor(size))\r\n    larger_threshold <- larger_size * n_larger\r\n    bins <- if_else(x <= larger_threshold, \r\n                    (x + (larger_size - 1L)) / larger_size,\r\n                    (x + (-larger_threshold + smaller_size - 1L)) / smaller_size + n_larger)\r\n    as.integer(floor(bins))\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\nx <- seq(.1,1,.1)\r\nntile_083(x, 10)\r\nntile_083(x, 100)\r\nntile_083(x, 1000)\r\n\r\nntile_100(x, 10)\r\nntile_100(x, 100)\r\nntile_100(x, 1000)\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "with a clean error message.\r\n\r\n## Original post\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if this is really a bug but may warrant a warning message / change in the documentation.\r\n\r\nIn the documentation for the [`tibble`](https://tibble.tidyverse.org/reference/tibble.html) function one of the examples says\r\n\r\n```r\r\n# Use := to create columns with names that start with a dot:\r\ntibble(.rows = 3)\r\n#> # A tibble: 3 x 0\r\ntibble(.rows := 3)\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n#>   .rows\r\n#>   <dbl>\r\n#> 1     3\r\n```\r\nHowever if a user actually creates a tibble with a column named `.rows` then grouping will later cause an error\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\nlibrary(rlang, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\n\r\n# this doesn't work\r\ndat <- tibble(x = 1:10, .rows := rep(c(\"bob\", \"george\"), 5))\r\ndat %>% group_by(.data$.rows)\r\n#> Error: Column name `.rows` must not be duplicated.\r\n\r\n# changing to another name beginning with a dot will work\r\ndat <- tibble(x = 1:10, .cows := rep(c(\"bob\", \"george\"), 5))\r\ndat %>% group_by(.data$.cows)\r\n#> # A tibble: 10 x 2\r\n#> # Groups:   .cows [2]\r\n#>        x .cows \r\n#>    <int> <chr> \r\n#>  1     1 bob   \r\n#>  2     2 george\r\n#>  3     3 bob   \r\n#>  4     4 george\r\n#>  5     5 bob   \r\n#>  6     6 george\r\n#>  7     7 bob   \r\n#>  8     8 george\r\n#>  9     9 bob   \r\n#> 10    10 george\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if this can be protected against but if not maybe it would be useful to have a warning next to the example.\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-06-18 by the [reprex package](https://reprex.tidyverse.org) (v0.3.0)<\/sup>\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n\r\n<summary>Session info<\/summary>\r\n\r\n``` r\r\ndevtools::session_info()\r\n#> ─ Session info #>     "body": "Closes #5428 \r\n\r\nThe `map()` and `as_tibble()` calls in `n_distinct()` are fairly slow when called repeatedly (added in https://github.com/tidyverse/dplyr/pull/5072).\r\n\r\nThis PR refactors `n_distinct()` to avoid tibble and `map()` and instead only use vctrs. I imagine this will be further improved with hybrid eval, but this should help significantly for now. I don't think it should change any behavior of `n_distinct()`.\r\n\r\nBelow is an adjusted example from #5428. It reduces the number of rows from 50,000,000 down to a more reasonable 500,000. The example there was a bit extreme to run on 50 million rows, but I imagine that it should at least work now.\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(tidyverse)\r\n\r\nset.seed(123)\r\ntable_size <- 500000\r\n\r\ndates <- seq(as.Date('2020/07/01'), as.Date('2020/07/18'), by = \"day\")\r\n\r\ntable_tbl <- tibble(\r\n  column_1 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  date = sample(x = dates, size = table_size, replace = TRUE),\r\n  column_3 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_4 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_5 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_6 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T),\r\n  column_7 = sample.int(n = 100, size = table_size, replace = T)\r\n)\r\n\r\ntbl <- group_by(table_tbl, column_1, date, column_3, column_4, column_5)\r\n```\r\n\r\n```r\r\n# before\r\nbench::mark(\r\n  expr = summarise(tbl, ndist = n_distinct(column_6, column_7), .groups = \"drop_last\")\r\n)\r\n#> Warning: Some expressions had a GC in every iteration; so filtering is disabled.\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 6\r\n#>   expression      min   median `itr/sec` mem_alloc `gc/sec`\r\n#>   <bch:expr> <bch:tm> <bch:tm>     <dbl> <bch:byt>    <dbl>\r\n#> 1 expr          1.76m    1.76m   0.00947     130MB     4.87\r\n\r\n# after\r\nbench::mark(\r\n  expr = summarise(tbl, ndist = n_distinct(column_6, column_7), .groups = \"drop_last\")\r\n)\r\n#> Warning: Some expressions had a GC in every iteration; so filtering is disabled.\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 6\r\n#>   expression      min   median `itr/sec` mem_alloc `gc/sec`\r\n#>   <bch:expr> <bch:tm> <bch:tm>     <dbl> <bch:byt>    <dbl>\r\n#> 1 expr          8.74s    8.74s     0.114     130MB     4.69\r\n```\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-07-21 by the [reprex package](https://reprex.tidyverse.org) (v0.3.0)<\/sup>",

#>     "body": "I'm sure there are some design decisions in the way `bind_rows()` handles `NA`, `NULL` and zero-length list elements when creating the final `tbl_df`. However, I would like to note the differences between `dplyr::bind_rows()`, `do.call(rbind, .)` and `data.table::rbindlist()` because it appears that {dplyr} has the most undesirable and unpredictable behavior of all 3 options.\r\n\r\nIn all of the test cases below I would, at minimum, expect the result to have 2 rows and 2 columns. Ideally, it would also preserve the column order based on the elements and replace all zero-length elements with NA (i.e. `NULL` and zero length vectors like `integer(0)` or `character()`).\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(data.table, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\nlibrary(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Happy path test case (preserves all elements as-is)**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = \"A\", b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\nbind_rows(l)\r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 A         1\r\n#> 2 B         2\r\n\r\ndo.call(rbind, l)\r\n#>      a   b\r\n#> [1,] \"A\" 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\" 2\r\n\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE)\r\n#>    a b\r\n#> 1: A 1\r\n#> 2: B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**All NA elements in a list (row)**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NA, b = NA)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 <NA>     NA\r\n#> 2 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a   b \r\n#> [1,] NA  NA\r\n#> [2,] \"B\" 2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#>       a  b\r\n#> 1: <NA> NA\r\n#> 2:    B  2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**All NULL elements in list**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NULL, b = NULL)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and retains NULL values\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a    b   \r\n#> [1,] NULL NULL\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"  2\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE)\r\n#>    a b\r\n#> 1: B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**A single NULL element**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = NULL, b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# preserves first row, but flips column order\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 2 x 2\r\n#>       b a    \r\n#>   <dbl> <chr>\r\n#> 1     1 <NA> \r\n#> 2     2 B\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and retains NULL value\r\ndo.call(rbind, l) \r\n#>      a    b\r\n#> [1,] NULL 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"  2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and returns NA value in place of NULL\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#> Warning in rbindlist(l, fill = TRUE): Column 1 ['a'] of item 1 is length 0. This\r\n#> (and 0 others like it) has been filled with NA (NULL for list columns) to make\r\n#> each item uniform.\r\n#>       a b\r\n#> 1: <NA> 1\r\n#> 2:    B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n**A single length zero element**\r\n``` r\r\nfirst_list <- list(a = character(0), b = 1)\r\nsecond_list <- list(a = \"B\", b = 2)\r\nl <- list(first_list, second_list)\r\n\r\n# drops first row\r\nbind_rows(l) \r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 2\r\n#>   a         b\r\n#>   <chr> <dbl>\r\n#> 1 B         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row\r\ndo.call(rbind, l)\r\n#>      a           b\r\n#> [1,] Character,0 1\r\n#> [2,] \"B\"         2\r\n\r\n# preserves first row and returns NA in place of zero-length element\r\nrbindlist(l, fill=TRUE) \r\n#> Warning in rbindlist(l, fill = TRUE): Column 1 ['a'] of item 1 is length 0. This\r\n#> (and 0 others like it) has been filled with NA (NULL for list columns) to make\r\n#> each item uniform.\r\n#>       a b\r\n#> 1: <NA> 1\r\n#> 2:    B 2\r\n```\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-07-21 by the [reprex package](https://reprex.tidyverse.org) (v0.3.0)<\/sup>\r\n",

#>     "body": "EDIT: @hadley identified the underlying issue is with grouping rather than summarize. See his post below\r\n\r\n\r\nWhile creating new columns using `mutate` or `summarize`, I'd like to be able to add the `label` attribute to each column so that I can add additional context to my columns at the time of creation. A useful [stackoverflow post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27347548/r-assign-variable-labels-of-data-frame-columns) supplied info on how to do this with `mutate`, however I've found that summarize drops the column attributes after creation (please see reprex below). \r\n\r\nHaving labels makes my data so much more understandable, and allows my customers (also R users) to get everything they need when using `view`/`View`:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"800\" alt=\"Screen Shot 2020-07-20 at 9 36 24 AM\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18296227/87962728-82535700-ca6c-11ea-921a-cf2d3dd36908.png\">\r\n \r\n---\r\n\r\nBrief description of the problem:\r\nWhile `mutate` and an ungrouped `summarize` maintain column attributes such as `label`, a grouped `summarize` does not.\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(magrittr)\r\nlibrary(tibble)\r\nlibrary(dplyr)\r\n#> \r\n#> Attaching package: 'dplyr'\r\n#> The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':\r\n#> \r\n#>     filter, lag\r\n#> The following objects are masked from 'package:base':\r\n#> \r\n#>     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union\r\nlibrary(Hmisc)\r\n#> Loading required package: lattice\r\n#> Loading required package: survival\r\n#> Loading required package: Formula\r\n#> Loading required package: ggplot2\r\n#> \r\n#> Attaching package: 'Hmisc'\r\n#> The following objects are masked from 'package:dplyr':\r\n#> \r\n#>     src, summarize\r\n#> The following objects are masked from 'package:base':\r\n#> \r\n#>     format.pval, units\r\n\r\nmtcars = tibble::as_tibble(mtcars)\r\n\r\n# Mutate works as expected\r\nmtcars %>%\r\n  dplyr::mutate(mpg_hp_ratio = mpg/hp %>% structure(label = 'Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio')) %>%\r\n  dplyr::pull() %>%\r\n  Hmisc::label()\r\n#> [1] \"Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio\"\r\n\r\n# Ungrouped summarize works as expected\r\nmtcars %>%\r\n  dplyr::summarise(mpg_hp_ratio = mpg/hp %>% structure(label = 'Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio')) %>%\r\n  dplyr::pull() %>%\r\n  Hmisc::label()\r\n#> [1] \"Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio\"\r\n\r\n# Grouped summarize does not keep the label\r\nmtcars %>%\r\n  dplyr::group_by(cyl) %>%\r\n  dplyr::summarise(mpg_hp_ratio = mean(mpg)/mean(hp) %>% structure(label = 'Average Miles per Gallon to Horse Power Ratio')) %>%\r\n  dplyr::pull() %>%\r\n  Hmisc::label()\r\n#> `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)\r\n#> [1] \"\"\r\n```\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on #>     "body": "Hi, \r\n\r\nIt would be great if join commands had the possibility to update values. \r\n\r\nFor example, I am working with data frame \"m\" and want to update the \"x\" values for some NA cases using another data frame \"y\".  Join commands will generate two columns x.x and x.y. Then, I would have to mutate values to update variables in this new, larger data.frame. \r\n\r\nHowever, if there was an update = T option, the new data.frame could automatically update NA values from the master data-set with the columns that have the same name in the using data set. Then, no new columns will be generated, I will be working in a smaller data-set and there would be no need to do any extra steps. \r\n\r\nThere could also be a conflict option to also manage the cases in which there are values in both the master and using data set. For example, if conflict = F, then when there are values in both master and using values then master data is retained, and nothing is changed in the column for rows that are present in master and using data. However, if conflict = T then the data from the using data set is retained. \r\n\r\nIn STATA this is part of the  [merge](https://www.stata.com/manuals13/dmerge.pdf) command. Some people have been asking the same and making some workarounds [example](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51572462/update-replace-values-in-dataframe-with-tidyverse-join). \r\n \r\nThank you once again for dplyr.\r\n\r\n```r\r\nm <- data.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x = c(4, 4, NA))\r\nu <- data.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x = c(5, 5, 5))\r\n\r\n# Current results\r\nm %>% full_join(u, by = \"id\")\r\n\r\n# With update = T we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(4,4,5))\r\n\r\n# With update = T and conflict = T we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(5,5,5))\r\n# With update = T and conflict = F we want:\r\ndata.frame(id  = c(1,2,3), x  = c(4,4,5))\r\n\r\n\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "---\r\n\r\nHey! I know that row names on tibbles are deprecated (which I disagree with but that is beside the point) but I think that for now, given that someone wants to continue using this deprecated feature, functions like mutate should not drop rownames in cases by default where the user wants to keep them.  There are constructs outside of the tidyverse that still use rownames; for example the bioconductor object 'eset' uses them in important ways and there are tools that take esets and not more modern bioconductor objects.   So if I want to use tibbles and dplyr verbs when constructing esets I have to do inconvenient workarounds, or not use dplyr.   So what I want is for tidyverse functions to preserve rownames wherever possible, even though I know it is not possible with certain things (like joins where rows are added). \r\n\r\n\r\nHere is a simple example: \r\n```r\r\nlibrary(tidyverse)\r\nsmall_tibble <- mpg[1:3,1:3]\r\nrownames(small_tibble) <- c(\"snap\",\"cracke\",\"pop\")\r\nprint(rownames(small_tibble)) #setting rownames was successful\r\nsmall_tibble_mutated <- small_tibble %>% mutate(displ = displ^2)\r\nprint(rownames(small_tibble_mutated)) #rownames disappeared\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "It would be incredible if you could specify which kind of duplicates in the join variable(s) is(are) acceptable as in [the STATA merge command](https://www.stata.com/manuals13/dmerge.pdf). \r\n\r\nThis means having the possibility to decide whether it's ok to have: \r\n- Duplicates in the join variables of the master data but not in the join variables of the using data (a m:1 join)\r\n- Duplicates in the join variables of the using data but not in the join variables of the master data (a 1:m join)\r\n- Duplicates in both cases (an m:m join)\r\n- No duplicates (a 1:1 join)\r\n\r\nI work in education, and some times data-sets were poorly digitized because some students appear to have been enrolled in more than one school (duplicates in the join variable).  When that happens both in the master and using data, those students multiply exponentially in the resulting data-frame, as it happens now with, for example, left_join.  You may not want that. Also, if you are not cautious enough, you may not pay attention to duplicate students, that \"ninjaly\" add more observations to your results. \r\n\r\nSTATA used to have the same issue and only had two commands \"merge\" or \"join\" somehow similar to R, and did not let you decide when duplicates are acceptable (i.e duplicate information in the using data when merging students to school characteristics, school id is the join variable) and when it may not be acceptable (i.e duplicate information in the master and using data when merging a student list to a student characteristic, student id is the join variable). At some point, they made that feature feasible and it's great because it allows you to merge and make quality control in one single step. \r\n\r\nThank you for your time and amazing work. Hope this helps. \r\n",

#>     "body": "With reference to https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62898859/how-can-i-use-dplyr-across-programmatically-on-no-variables/62901180#62901180 compute_mean1 gives an error but compute_mean2 and compute_mean3 give the expected answer.   compute_mean1 uses across and fails, coimpute_mean2 uses group_by_at and works while compute_mean3 is the same as coimpute_mean1 but also has the argument .add=TRUE and gives the expected answer. Surely this should work even if .add = FALSE.\r\n\r\n```\r\ncompute_mean1 <- function(df, grouping) { # compute grouped mean with across()\r\n  df %>% \r\n    group_by(across(all_of(grouping))) %>% \r\n    summarise(y = mean(y), .groups = \"drop\")\r\n}\r\n\r\ncompute_mean2 <- function(df, grouping) { # compute grouped mean with group_by_at()\r\n  df %>% \r\n    group_by_at(grouping) %>% \r\n    summarise(y = mean(y), .groups = \"drop\")\r\n}\r\n\r\ncompute_mean3 <- function(df, grouping) { # compute grouped mean with across()\r\n  df %>% \r\n    group_by(across(all_of(grouping)), .add = TRUE) %>%\r\n    summarise(y = mean(y), .groups = \"drop\")\r\n}\r\n\r\nlibrary(dplyr)\r\n\r\nmy_df <- tibble(\"x\" = c(\"a\", \"a\", \"b\", \"b\"), y = 1:4)\r\n\r\ncompute_mean1(my_df, NULL)\r\n\r\ncompute_mean2(my_df, NULL)\r\n\r\ncompute_mean3(my_df, NULL)\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "The ntile() function in dplyr 1.0.0 gives different results than in version 0.8.3.  Looking at the function code, it has changed a great deal.  I show both functions in my reprex.  ntile_083 scales us as the value of n increases, but ntile1_100 does not, its output is invariant to n (as long as n >= x).  This is a big change in the output.  Was this the intented result?\r\n\r\n```r\r\nntile_083 <- function (x = row_number(), n) {\r\n  len <- sum(!is.na(x))\r\n  if (len == 0L) {\r\n    rep(NA_integer_, length(x))\r\n  } else {\r\n    as.integer(floor(n * (row_number(x) - 1)/len + 1))\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\nntile_100 <- function (x = row_number(), n) {\r\n  if (!missing(x)) {\r\n    x <- row_number(x)\r\n  }\r\n  len <- length(x) - sum(is.na(x))\r\n  n <- as.integer(floor(n))\r\n  if (len == 0L) {\r\n    rep(NA_integer_, length(x))\r\n  } else {\r\n    n_larger <- as.integer(len%%n)\r\n    n_smaller <- as.integer(n - n_larger)\r\n    size <- len/n\r\n    larger_size <- as.integer(ceiling(size))\r\n    smaller_size <- as.integer(floor(size))\r\n    larger_threshold <- larger_size * n_larger\r\n    bins <- if_else(x <= larger_threshold, \r\n                    (x + (larger_size - 1L)) / larger_size,\r\n                    (x + (-larger_threshold + smaller_size - 1L)) / smaller_size + n_larger)\r\n    as.integer(floor(bins))\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\nx <- seq(.1,1,.1)\r\nntile_083(x, 10)\r\nntile_083(x, 100)\r\nntile_083(x, 1000)\r\n\r\nntile_100(x, 10)\r\nntile_100(x, 100)\r\nntile_100(x, 1000)\r\n```\r\n",

#>     "body": "with a clean error message.\r\n\r\n## Original post\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if this is really a bug but may warrant a warning message / change in the documentation.\r\n\r\nIn the documentation for the [`tibble`](https://tibble.tidyverse.org/reference/tibble.html) function one of the examples says\r\n\r\n```r\r\n# Use := to create columns with names that start with a dot:\r\ntibble(.rows = 3)\r\n#> # A tibble: 3 x 0\r\ntibble(.rows := 3)\r\n#> # A tibble: 1 x 1\r\n#>   .rows\r\n#>   <dbl>\r\n#> 1     3\r\n```\r\nHowever if a user actually creates a tibble with a column named `.rows` then grouping will later cause an error\r\n\r\n``` r\r\nlibrary(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\nlibrary(rlang, warn.conflicts = FALSE)\r\n\r\n# this doesn't work\r\ndat <- tibble(x = 1:10, .rows := rep(c(\"bob\", \"george\"), 5))\r\ndat %>% group_by(.data$.rows)\r\n#> Error: Column name `.rows` must not be duplicated.\r\n\r\n# changing to another name beginning with a dot will work\r\ndat <- tibble(x = 1:10, .cows := rep(c(\"bob\", \"george\"), 5))\r\ndat %>% group_by(.data$.cows)\r\n#> # A tibble: 10 x 2\r\n#> # Groups:   .cows [2]\r\n#>        x .cows \r\n#>    <int> <chr> \r\n#>  1     1 bob   \r\n#>  2     2 george\r\n#>  3     3 bob   \r\n#>  4     4 george\r\n#>  5     5 bob   \r\n#>  6     6 george\r\n#>  7     7 bob   \r\n#>  8     8 george\r\n#>  9     9 bob   \r\n#> 10    10 george\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'm not sure if this can be protected against but if not maybe it would be useful to have a warning next to the example.\r\n\r\n<sup>Created on 2020-06-18 ## Use I() to force body part to be sent as an array, even if length 1
## This works whether assignees has length 1 or > 1
assignees <- "gh_user"
assignees <- c("gh_user1", "gh_user2")
gh("PATCH /repos/OWNER/REPO/issues/1", assignees = I(assignees))
}) # examplesIf
if (FALSE) (if (getRversion() >= "3.4") withAutoprint else force)({ # examplesIf
## There are two ways to send JSON data. One is that you supply one or
## more objects that will be converted to JSON automatically via
## jsonlite::toJSON(). In this case sometimes you need to use
## jsonlite::unbox() because fromJSON() creates lists from scalar vectors
## by default. The Content-Type header is automatically added in this
## case. For example this request turns on GitHub Pages, using this
## API: https://developer.github.com/v3/repos/pages/#enable-a-pages-site

gh::gh(
  "POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/pages",
  owner = "gaborcsardi",
  repo = "playground",
  source = list(
    branch = jsonlite::unbox("master"),
    path = jsonlite::unbox("/docs")
  ),
  .send_headers = c(Accept = "application/vnd.github.switcheroo-preview+json")
)

## The second way is to handle the JSON encoding manually, and supply it
## as a raw vector in an unnamed argument, and also a Content-Type header:

body <- '{ "source": { "branch": "master", "path": "/docs" } }'
gh::gh(
  "POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/pages",
  owner = "gaborcsardi",
  repo = "playground",
  charToRaw(body),
  .send_headers = c(
    Accept = "application/vnd.github.switcheroo-preview+json",
    "Content-Type" = "application/json"
  )
)
}) # examplesIf
